    "explanation": "The Luni River of Rajasthan originates from Naga Hill, located in the Aravalli Range near Ajmer. Initially, it is known as Sagarmati, and after its tributary Sarasuti, which originates from Pushkar Lake, joins it, it is called the Luni River. Fresh water is found in the upper part of its course, but on reaching Balotra, its water becomes saline or salty because the surface along its course there is rich in salts. This river flows in the south-west direction and merges into the Rann of Kachchh. Thus, it is an inland river. Because of the salinity of its water, it is called Luni (Rajasthani–Luni). This name is derived from the Sanskrit word Lavanavati (Salt River).",
