    "answer": [
     "b"
    ],
    "disputed": false,
    "source": "U.P.P.C.S. (Pre) 2006",
    "explanation": "Based on the data provided by the India Meteorological Department (IMD) and other agencies, the Bureau of Indian Standards prepared the Earthquake Resistant Design Code of India (IS 1893 Part 1: 2002), which is the latest version of the Seismic Zoning Map of India. In this, the territory of India has been divided into four zones from the point of view of earthquake proneness. Seismic Zone Intensity II (Low-intensity zone) VI (or less) – Low Damage III (Moderate-intensity zone) VII – Damage to Buildings IV (Severe-intensity zone) VIII – Destruction of Buildings V (Very high-intensity zone) I X (and above) – Very High Damage Zone V - Under the IS Code, this zone has been assigned a zone factor of 0.36. This means that, due to an earthquake, a structure in this zone may experience horizontal acceleration up to 36 percent of gravitational acceleration. It is a very high-damage-risk zone. Jammu and Kashmir and Ladakh, Himachal Pradesh, Uttarakhand, parts of Bihar, the Rann of Kachchh, the Andaman and Nicobar Islands, and the northeastern region fall in this zone. About 10.9 percent of the country’s total land area lies in this zone. Zone IV - Its zone factor under the IS Code is 0.24. It includes the Indo-Gangetic Plain region, including the national capital Delhi, the rest of the Himalayan region, parts of Gujarat, the Koyna region of Maharashtra, Sikkim, etc. About 17.3 percent of the country’s total land area falls in this zone. Zone III - Its zone factor is 0.16. Lakshadweep, the Western Ghats, the faulted region of Peninsular India, and the southern part of the Gangetic Plains, including Lucknow, the capital of Uttar Pradesh, fall in this zone. This zone covers about 30.4 percent of India’s land area. Zone II - Its zone factor is 0.10. The earlier Zones I and II have now been merged into the present Zone II. About 41.4 percent of India’s total land area falls in this zone. Most of the Peninsular Plateau lies in this zone. The Karnataka Plateau is also part of the Peninsular Plateau. Therefore, it is included in the zone with the lowest seismic risk.",
