    "explanation": "The shadow of an object depends mainly on the altitude of the Sun and the angle at which the Sun’s rays fall on the object. The shortest shadow is formed when the Sun is at the greatest height in the sky. On the date of the Summer Solstice, 20/21 June, at exactly 12 noon, the Sun shines vertically over the Tropic of Cancer. At such places, little or no shadow is formed. If the Earth were flat everywhere, then at all places on the Tropic of Cancer at 12 noon on 20/21 June, no shadow would be formed. But because the Earth is curved, places away from the exact position form a greater angle, and some shadow is produced. As the distance from the Tropic of Cancer increases, the size of the shadow also changes. In the Northern Hemisphere, on 20/21 June, it is minimum as compared to other days.",
